DECLARE
  v_test_id UUID;
  v_section_id UUID;
  v_passage_id UUID;
  v_qorder INT;
BEGIN
  -- Create test
  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), 'Cambridge IELTS 16 - Reading Test 4', 'cambridge-ielts-16-reading-test-4', 'PUBLISHED', 60, '11111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111', NOW(), NOW())
  RETURNING id INTO v_test_id;
  

  -- ═══════ SECTION 1: Passage 1 — Roman Tunnels ═══════
  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), v_test_id, 'Passage 1 — Roman Tunnels', 'READING', 0)
  RETURNING id INTO v_section_id;

  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), v_section_id, E'Roman Tunnels\n\nThe fruit of the Persians'' work was the qanat, a gently sloping tunnel that carried water from an underground water source to the surface, irrigating fields along the way. The qanat was an important technological development as it relied on gravity rather than mechanical pumps. In the early first millennium BCE, the Persians introduced the qanat method of tunnel construction, which consisted of placing posts over a hill in a straight line, to ensure that the tunnel kept to its route. Vertical shafts were sunk at regular intervals along the line and the tunnel was excavated from the bottom of each shaft.\n\nThe Romans, too, were great tunnel builders. A key Roman technique was to work from both ends of a tunnel at once. In terms of accuracy, perhaps the finest example of ancient tunnel engineering is the tunnel on the Greek island of Samos, built in the sixth century BCE. Designed by the engineer Eupalinos, the one-kilometre tunnel was dug from both ends and the two halves met in the middle with only a small margin of error. This was a remarkable feat of surveying.\n\nModern tunnel building relies on technology that would have been unimaginable to ancient engineers. Tunnel boring machines (TBMs), which can excavate tunnels with diameters up to 17 metres, use a large rotating cutter head to break through rock and soil. The Channel Tunnel, linking Britain and France beneath the English Channel, was completed in 1994 using eleven TBMs. At 50 kilometres, it is one of the longest underwater tunnels in the world and carries both rail passengers and freight.\n\nMore recently, Elon Musk''s Boring Company has proposed the development of a network of underground tunnels in cities such as Los Angeles to help alleviate traffic congestion. The company claims that its machines can bore tunnels at significantly lower costs than traditional methods, although critics question whether the approach is practical on a large scale.', 1)
  RETURNING id INTO v_passage_id;

  v_qorder := 1;
  -- Gap fills

  -- True/False/Not Given

  -- MCQ

  -- ═══════ SECTION 2: Passage 2 — Reading in a Whole New Way ═══════
  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), v_test_id, 'Passage 2 — Reading in a Whole New Way', 'READING', 1)
  RETURNING id INTO v_section_id;

  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), v_section_id, E'Reading in a Whole New Way\n\nLook around on your next plane trip. The iPad is the new pacifier for babies and toddlers. Younger school-aged children read stories on smartphones; older kids don''t read at all, but hunch over video games. Parents and other passengers read on tablets or skim a flotilla of email and news feeds. Unbeknown to most of us, an invisible, game-changing transformation links everyone in this picture: the neuronal circuit that underlies the brain''s ability to read is subtly, rapidly changing — and this has implications for everyone from the pre-reading toddler to the expert adult.\n\nThe act of reading is not natural. We were never born to read. Human beings invented literacy only a few thousand years ago. And with this invention, we rearranged the very organisation of our brain, which in turn expanded the ways we were able to think, which altered the intellectual evolution of our species. The reading circuit is not given to us through a genetic blueprint like vision or language; it needs an environment to develop. Furthermore, it will adapt to that environment''s requirements — from different writing systems used across cultures to the predominant medium in which the written word is presented. If the dominant medium of our time is digital, the reading circuit will adapt accordingly.\n\nThe problem is that many features of the current digital environment work against deep reading processes. For example, the sheer volume of information and the speed at which we are expected to process it militate against the kind of slow, deliberate, cognitively demanding processes that compose a significant portion of the reading circuit: critical analysis, the development of personal insight, and reflection. There is an emerging body of research that indicates that reading on screens promotes a shift in cognitive patterns from deep reading to speed reading, skimming, and word-spotting.\n\nMaryanne Wolf, a cognitive neuroscientist at Tufts University, has long studied the science of the reading brain. Wolf argues that we should not assume that critical analysis, empathy, and other deep reading processes will transfer automatically from a print-based reading brain to one that has adapted to screen-based reading. In her view, we need to cultivate a "bi-literate" brain — one that is equally capable of deep reading on paper and efficient reading on screens.', 1)
  RETURNING id INTO v_passage_id;

  -- MCQ

  -- T/F/NG

  -- Gap fills

  -- ═══════ SECTION 3: Passage 3 — AI and Predictions ═══════
  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), v_test_id, 'Passage 3 — AI and Predictions', 'READING', 2)
  RETURNING id INTO v_section_id;

  VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), v_section_id, E'The Future of Artificial Intelligence in Forecasting\n\nArtificial intelligence is now capable of predicting the future — at least in certain well-defined areas. AI systems can forecast which patients are likely to develop specific diseases, which convicted criminals are likely to reoffend, which students are at risk of dropping out, and even which couples are heading for divorce. In many cases, their predictions are significantly more accurate than those made by human experts working in the same fields.\n\nPolice departments in several US cities, for example, have adopted predictive policing software. These systems use machine learning algorithms to analyze historical crime data and identify "hot spots" where crimes are most likely to occur. Researchers have found that such algorithms outperform experienced crime analysts at forecasting where burglaries and car thefts are most likely to happen.\n\nIn medicine, AI systems have shown promising results in predicting health outcomes. An algorithm developed at Stanford University can examine a chest X-ray and diagnose pneumonia more accurately than a panel of expert radiologists. Similarly, Google''s DeepMind has developed an AI system that can predict acute kidney injury up to 48 hours before it occurs — potentially giving doctors crucial time to intervene.\n\nDespite these impressive achievements, people remain reluctant to trust AI predictions. Studies consistently show that when given the choice, most individuals prefer to rely on human judgment, even when they are told that the algorithm is more accurate. This phenomenon has been termed "algorithm aversion." Researchers have found that people lose confidence in an algorithm more quickly after seeing it make a mistake than they would lose confidence in a human expert who made the same error.\n\nIf AI is to benefit society by improving predictions across domains, researchers must first understand why people resist algorithmic recommendations. Only by addressing the psychological barriers to the adoption of AI predictions can we hope to harness the full potential of these powerful tools.', 1)
  RETURNING id INTO v_passage_id;

  -- MCQ

  -- T/F/NG

  -- Gap fills

  RAISE NOTICE 'Reading test created with ID: %', v_test_id;
END $$;
